        <h2>How It All Began</h2>
        <p>
            The Central Utah Tree Festival was born from a simple observation: when children in our rural
            community need specialized medical care, their families face an impossible choice between
            their child's health and their family's financial stability.
        </p>
        <p>
            In 2024, a group of neighbors and friends in Sanpete County came together with a vision—to
            create something beautiful that could make a real difference. We knew our community was full
            of generous hearts, creative spirits, and people who care deeply about their neighbors. The
            Central Utah Tree Festival became our way of channeling that love into meaningful support.
        </p>
        <div class="quote-box">
            "What started as a conversation around a kitchen table has grown into an annual tradition
            that brings our entire community together in support of our most vulnerable families."
        </div>
        <p>
            From that first festival, we've been amazed by the creativity, generosity, and compassion
            of our community. Every decorated tree tells a story. Every bid at our auction represents
            hope. Every volunteer hour is an investment in a child's future.
        </p>
    </section>

    <!-- The Problem We're Solving -->
    <section class="content-section">
        <h2>The Journey No Family Should Face Alone</h2>
        <p>
            Living in rural Sanpete County offers many blessings—tight-knit communities, beautiful
            landscapes, and a quality of life many people dream of. But when a child faces a serious
            medical condition, that rural setting becomes a challenge.
        </p>
        <p>
            Primary Children's Hospital in Salt Lake City is one of the nation's premier pediatric
            medical centers, offering specialized care that can mean the difference between life and
            death for critically ill children. For families in Sanpete County, accessing that care
            means traveling over 100 miles each way.
        </p>

        <h3>The Hidden Costs of Distance</h3>
        <p>
            When a child needs ongoing treatment, those miles add up to more than just inconvenience:
        </p>
        <div class="stats-grid">
            <div class="stat-item">
                <span class="stat-number">120+ Miles</span>
                <span class="stat-label">Round trip to Salt Lake City</span>
